The visdat package makes ggplot compatible missingness plots. The cluster = TRUE option groups varaibles that share missingness. Here we see that usually if some of the github data is missing, then all of the GitHub data is missing. The percent missing is listed for each variable and the overall missingness of the dataset is shown in the legend.

Note vis_miss doesn't work on very large datasets. The documentations suggests keeping the number of records below 1,000. There is a more extensive package for exploratory visualizations called naniar which could also be used.


::: {.cell .column-page}

```{.r .cell-code}
languages_numeric %>%
vis_miss(cluster = TRUE) +
ggtitle("Missing Data in the Languages Dataset") +
  #theme_classic() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(size = 8, angle = 90))
```

